{{Infobox museum | name = Living Torah Museum | image = It is the front site of the Living Torah Museum.jpg | imagesize = | caption = | alt = | map_type = USA New York City | map_size = | map_caption = Location within New York City | coordinates = {{coord|40.635556|-73.980833|region:US-NY|display=inline,title}} | established = | location = 1601 41st street, Brooklyn, New York | type = | accreditation = | key_holdings = | collections = | collection = | visitors = | director = | president = | curator = | owner = | publictransit = '''Subway''': [[File:NYCS-bull-trans-F.svg|20px]] [[Ditmas Avenue (IND Culver Line)|Ditmas Avenue]] | car_park = | network = | website = {{URL|http://www.thelivingtorahmuseum.com/}} }} The '''Living Torah Museum''' is a group of [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jewish]] [[museum]]s that opened in 2002 and drew approximately 600,000 visitors in the first twelve years.<ref name="jwe"/> The museums were founded and are operated by rabbi and author [[Shaul Shimon Deutsch]]. The first location is at 1601 41st street in [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Borough Park]], [[Brooklyn, New York]], United States and was named a Best Museum of New York by the [[Village Voice]].<ref name="obs"/> A second location, in the [[Catskill Mountains]] town of [[Fallsburg, New York]], operates during the summer season. A third location, which was open year-round in [[Lakewood, New Jersey]], closed in 2014.<ref name="jwe">{{cite news|last1=Weichselbaum|first1=Lehman|title=Living Torah Museum Faces Financial Dificulties|url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new-york/living-torah-museum-faces-financial-dificulties|accessdate=11 November 2016|work=Jewish Week|date=2014-03-24}}</ref>
